{"cursor":"4034","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Thomas G. Bever image = Tom Bever.jpg image_size = alt = caption =\n| birth_date = birth_place = death_date = \n| death_place = residence = citizenship = nationality = fields =\n| Psycholinguistics, Neurolinguistics, Language acquisition workplaces =\n| University of Arizona, University of Rochester, Columbia University alma_mater\n| = MIT, Harvard doctoral_advisor = Morris Halle academic_advisors =\n| doctoral_students = notable_students = known_for = author_abbrev_bot =\n| author_abbrev_zoo = influences = influenced = awards = signature =  signature_alt = footnotes =\n}}\n\n'Thomas G. Bever' (born December 9, 1939) is a Regent's Professor of Psychology,\nLinguistics, Cognitive Science, and Neuroscience at the University of Arizona.\nHe has been a leading figure in psycholinguistics, focusing on the cognitive and\nneurological bases of linguistic universals, among other pursuits. Bever\nreceived a B.A. in linguistics and psychology from Harvard University in 1961,\nand a Ph.D. in linguistics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in\n1967; he studied with Noam Chomsky and Jean Piaget. He taught at Rockefeller\nUniversity from 1967â1969, Columbia University from 1970â1986 (where he was\ninvolved with Project Nim), and the University of Rochester from 1985â1995,\nbefore accepting his current position at the University of Arizona, where he has\nremained ever since.\n\nBever is notable for his study of garden path sentences such as The horse raced\npast the barn fell, Bever, T.G (1970). The cognitive basis for linguistic\nstructures. In: J.R. Hayes, Editor, Cognition and the development of language,\nWiley, New York (1970), pp. 279â362. as well as his analysis by synthesis\nmodel of sentence processing, developed with David Townsend. Townsend, David\nJ., and Thomas G. Bever (2001). Sentence Comprehension: The Integration of\nHabits and Rules. MIT Press In recent decades, Bever has studied the\ndifferences in language processing between righthanders with familial handedness\nand righthanders without left-handed relatives. He was a co-founder\nof the journal 'Cognition.'\n","linknr":146,"url":"Thomas_Bever","recorded":1375088683,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Thomas_Bever&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Thomas_Bever&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Tom_Bever.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6d/Tom_Bever.jpg/220px-Tom_Bever.jpg","/wiki/Psycholinguistics","/wiki/Neurolinguistics","/wiki/Language_acquisition","/wiki/University_of_Arizona","/wiki/University_of_Rochester","/wiki/Columbia_University","/wiki/Alma_mater","/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology","/wiki/Harvard_University","/wiki/Doctoral_advisor","/wiki/Morris_Halle","/wiki/Professor","/wiki/Psychology","/wiki/Linguistics","/wiki/Cognitive_Science","/wiki/Neuroscience","/wiki/University_of_Arizona","/wiki/Psycholinguistics","/wiki/Linguistic_universals","/wiki/Bachelor_of_Arts","/wiki/Linguistics","/wiki/Psychology","/wiki/Harvard_University","/wiki/Ph.D.","/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology","/wiki/Noam_Chomsky","/wiki/Jean_Piaget","/wiki/Rockefelle